<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="265" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[1392,2604,1358,2136]" pageId="4" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1393,1644,1440,1465]" pageId="4" pageNumber="265">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 180-220 mm, tail 125-150 mm, ear 13-17 mm, hindfoot 43-45 mm. No specific data are available for body weight. The Golden-bellied Treeshrew is large; dorsum is uniform brown, with tinges of red; and venteris lighter, with tan hue. Tail has short hair, ¢.10 mm in length, and diagnostic light shoulder marking seen in many tupaiids is faint in some specimens and absent in others.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="265" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[1392,2604,1358,2136]" pageId="4" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1393,1504,1633,1662]" pageId="4" pageNumber="265">Habitat.</emphasis>
[Lowland primary rainforests on four Mentawai Islands at elevations up to 1000 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="265" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph blockId="4.[1392,2604,1358,2136]" pageId="4" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1394,1657,1712,1741]" pageId="4" pageNumber="265">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
There is no specific information available for this species, but the Golden-bellied Treeshrew is presumably a generalist based on cranial morphology.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
